    <section id="cardiovascular-risk" class="reveal">
      <h2>Cardiovascular Risk: The Post-Menopause Surge</h2>

      <p>The cardiovascular risk profile of women changes dramatically after menopause, and this change is one of the most practically consequential — and least understood — aspects of women's health.</p>

      <p>Before menopause, women have substantially lower rates of heart disease than age-matched men. This protection is largely attributable to estrogen's effects on lipid metabolism (raising HDL, lowering LDL), vascular function (promoting arterial elasticity and vasodilation through nitric oxide pathways), and anti-inflammatory signaling in the vascular endothelium.</p>

      <p>After menopause, these protections withdraw. LDL rises, HDL falls, arterial stiffness increases, and visceral fat accumulates — a cluster of changes that shifts women's cardiovascular risk profile toward the male pattern and, in many cases, beyond it. Women who undergo premature menopause (before age 40) have a 40% higher lifetime risk of coronary heart disease than women who experience menopause at the typical age — a finding that quantifies, in stark terms, how much cardiovascular protection the ovary provides.</p>

      <p>The clinical response to this shift has been, historically, inadequate. Women's cardiovascular disease presents later and with more atypical symptoms than men's, leading to systematic underdiagnosis. Women are less likely to receive aggressive intervention at presentation. And the menopause-driven risk elevation has not been systematically incorporated into cardiovascular risk calculators that inform treatment decisions.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Women who undergo premature menopause before age 40 have a 40% higher lifetime risk of coronary heart disease — quantifying, in stark terms, how much cardiovascular protection the ovary provides."</p>
