    <section id="bone-muscle-metabolic" class="reveal">
      <h2>Bone, Muscle, and the Metabolic Cascade</h2>

      <p>The skeletal consequences of estrogen loss are well-established: bone resorption accelerates sharply in the first few years after menopause, with women losing an average of 1-2% of bone density per year during this window. Lifetime fracture risk for postmenopausal women substantially exceeds that of same-age men. Hip fractures in particular carry a mortality rate often described as comparable to some cancers.</p>

      <p>Less discussed is the muscle story. Estrogen supports skeletal muscle mass and function through direct receptor-mediated effects on muscle fiber maintenance and protein synthesis. Menopause is associated with accelerated sarcopenia — age-related muscle loss — that is independent of physical activity level. This loss compounds the fall risk from bone density reduction and the metabolic consequences of reduced lean mass.</p>

      <p>The metabolic consequences include: reduced insulin sensitivity (increasing type 2 diabetes risk), increased visceral fat accumulation (driving inflammation), and altered energy expenditure patterns that make weight management progressively more difficult through mechanisms that are not simply behavioral.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="hormone-therapy" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Revised Hormone Therapy Evidence</h2>

      <p>The current state of the evidence on hormone therapy is more favorable than the post-WHI consensus allowed, with important nuances:</p>

      <p><strong>For whom:</strong> Women with significant menopausal symptoms who are under 60, within 10 years of menopause onset, and without contraindications (active breast cancer, unexplained vaginal bleeding, history of blood clots in some formulations) are generally considered appropriate candidates. The risk-benefit calculation changes after this window.</p>

      <p><strong>Formulation matters:</strong> Transdermal estrogen delivery (patches, gels, creams) does not carry the same blood clot risk as oral estrogen, because it bypasses first-pass liver metabolism. Micronized progesterone appears to have a more favorable breast safety profile than older synthetic progestins. The specific formulation, not just the class, is clinically relevant.</p>

      <p><strong>What it does:</strong> In the appropriate window, hormone therapy effectively reduces vasomotor symptoms (hot flashes and night sweats), reduces bone loss, improves sleep quality, supports cognitive function, and may reduce cardiovascular risk through the metabolic mechanisms described above. Longevity benefits are most established for premature menopause.</p>

      <p><strong>What remains uncertain:</strong> The long-term cancer risk data from modern formulations via transdermal delivery is still accumulating. Individualized risk assessment is genuinely necessary, not a pro forma disclaimer.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="research-gap" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Research Gap as Policy Problem</h2>

      <p>The fundamental issue is that women's health research has been systematically under-resourced relative to its burden. Conditions specific to or disproportionately affecting women have received less funding, less investigator attention, and less clinical attention than their population impact warrants. Endometriosis, covered elsewhere in this series, is a stark example — but the menopause story is in some respects even larger in scale, because it affects every woman who lives past her 50s.</p>

      <p>The effect of this neglect is that an estimated 47 million women in the United States alone are currently in some stage of perimenopause or postmenopause, many experiencing symptoms that affect their work, relationships, and daily function, and many receiving clinical responses that range from inadequate to dismissive.</p>

      <p>The science is catching up. The longevity research community — which has historically been male-dominated in both its research subjects and its practitioners — is visibly reorienting toward women's biology. New clinical trials, new biomarkers, and a new generation of researchers focused specifically on the ovarian aging process are generating knowledge at a rate that would have seemed unlikely a decade ago.</p>

      <p>Whether the clinical culture and the healthcare system catch up at the same rate is a different question, with a less certain answer.</p>
    </section>

